      The Elon texts
   =20
 =20

A good starting point for thinking about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s decision to bu=
y Twitter Inc., back in April, is that it did not involve any spreadsheets.=
 Like, when Musk decided to offer $54.20 per share to buy Twitter, that was=
 not based on any detailed financial modeling; Musk=E2=80=99s offers to buy=
 companies are generally pretty whimsical, and 420 is a weed joke. Eventual=
ly, as the deal started to go bad,   Musk demanded that Twitter send him=C2=
=A0its=C2=A0bankers=E2=80=99 working financial model, which is pretty unusu=
al in big public mergers and acquisitions,=C2=A0and suggests that Musk migh=
t not have had a working model of his own.
  [1]
=C2=A0Why would he?
Similarly, after Musk announced that he wanted to buy Twitter, he went look=
ing for financing, including equity financing: He wanted other people to in=
vest in the deal alongside him. Last week,  an assortment of text messages =
from Musk=E2=80=99s phone became public as part of the preparation for the =
trial, later this month, about whether Musk can get out of the deal he sign=
ed in April. Some of these texts are Musk=E2=80=99s friends, acquaintances =
and strangers texting him to say =E2=80=9Chey can I invest with you=E2=80=
=9D and Musk saying =E2=80=9CI would love that=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csure wh=
atever=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cno, not you,=E2=80=9D as the case may be. The g=
eneral approach is refreshingly casual. Here are=C2=A0Musk and Larry Elliso=
n on April 20 (the day that Musk delivered  his financing commitments to Tw=
itter):

Musk: Roughly what dollar size? Not holding you to anything, but the deal i=
s oversubscribed,=C2=A0so I have to reduce or kick out some participants.
Ellison: A billion =E2=80=A6=C2=A0or whatever you recommend
Musk: Whatever works for you. I=E2=80=99d recommend maybe $2B or more. This=
 has very high potential and I=E2=80=99d rather have you than anyone else.
Ellison: I agree that it has huge potential =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and it would be =
lots of fun.
Musk: Absolutely :)

Ellison  came in for $1 billion. =E2=80=9CThe deal is oversubscribed=E2=80=
=9D is just sort of a figure of speech.=C2=A0Obviously the deal was not ove=
rsubscribed, and in fact a month later Musk was still openly  hunting for m=
ore equity investors. But it would be weird not=C2=A0to say =E2=80=9Cthe de=
al is oversubscribed=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0it would sound desperate=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0so Musk did.
Or here is Michael Grimes, Musk=E2=80=99s lead banker at Morgan Stanley, pi=
tching him on crypto mogul Sam Bankman-Fried on April 25 (the day he signed=
 the deal to buy Twitter):

Grimes: Sam Bankman-Fried is why I=E2=80=99m calling. =E2=80=A6
Musk: ???
Musk: I=E2=80=99m backlogged with a mountain of critical work matters. Is t=
his urgent?
Grimes: Wants 1-5b. Serious about partner w/you. Same security you own. =E2=
=80=A6
Grimes: Could do 5bn if everything vision lock. Would do the engineering fo=
r social media blockchain integration. Founded FTX crypto exchange. Believe=
s in your mission. Major Democratic donor. So thought it was potentially wo=
rth an hour tomorrow a la the Orlando meeting and he said he could shake ha=
nds on 5 if you like him and I think you will. Can talk when you have more =
time not urgent but if tomorrow works out it could get us 5bn equity in an =
hour.

Musk replied by hitting the =E2=80=9Cdislike=E2=80=9D tapback button. (To b=
e fair, he also replied that =E2=80=9CBlockchain twitter isn=E2=80=99t poss=
ible,=E2=80=9D agreed to meet =E2=80=9Cso long as I don=E2=80=99t have to h=
ave a laborious blockchain debate,=E2=80=9D and asked if Bankman-Fried actu=
ally had $3 billion liquid. Ultimately Bankman-Fried and FTX never signed c=
ommitments to invest in Twitter, though Binance, another crypto exchange, w=
as in for $500 million.) The point I want to make here is that Elon Musk ha=
s attained=C2=A0a level of wealth and power where sometimes he gets text me=
ssages offering him $5 billion and he=C2=A0replies with a thumbs-down and m=
oves on with his day.
People got mad about these texts?  Charlie Warzel:
In no time, the texts were the central subject of discussion among tech wor=
kers and watchers. =E2=80=9CThe dominant reaction from all the threads I=E2=
=80=99m in is Everyone looks ... dumb,=E2=80=9D one former social-media exe=
cutive, whom I=E2=80=99ve granted anonymity because they have relationships=
 with many of the people in Musk=E2=80=99s texts, told me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s been a general Is this really how business is done? There=E2=80=99s=
 no real strategic thought or analysis. It=E2=80=99s just emotional and don=
e without any real care for consequence.=E2=80=9D
I dunno. How=C2=A0should=C2=A0people be doing business over text messaging?=
 On April 17, as Musk was publicly pressuring Twitter=E2=80=99s board with =
a semi-hostile takeover bid, the chairman of the board, Bret Taylor, reache=
d out to him by text to say =E2=80=9CElon, I am just checking in to reitera=
te that the board is seriously reviewing the proposal in your letter. We ar=
e working on a formal response as quickly as we can consistent with our fid=
uciary duties. Feel free to reach out anytime.=E2=80=9D Formal, serious, fu=
ll sentences, reviewed by a lawyer: very much Business Texting. Musk replie=
d with the =E2=80=9Clike=E2=80=9D tapback. How else should he have replied?=
 Yes, right, fiduciary duties, gotcha, thumbs up. He is doing big business,=
 but he=E2=80=99s also texting. The thumbs-up button is right there.
These texts make sense to me. There is a popular sense about=C2=A0Twitter t=
hat it is:
=09Tremendously important to society, the place where memes are made, an ar=
biter of political fortunes, =E2=80=9Cthe public square,=E2=80=9D an addict=
ion for rich and powerful people, and in many ways the most important websi=
te in the world; and also=09just a disorganized unmanaged mess.

=E2=80=9CA clown car that fell into a gold mine,=E2=80=9D is  Mark Zuckerbe=
rg=E2=80=99s famous phrase, but these days no one would emphasize the gold =
mine. This is a website that the world=E2=80=99s richest person, Elon Musk,=
 and the former president of the US, Donald Trump, are obsessed with, a web=
site with immense geopolitical power, and it makes money by serving not par=
ticularly well-targeted text ads and dithers for years about questions like=
 whether you should be able to edit tweets.=C2=A0
It is very common in the circles I run in =E2=80=94=C2=A0people who write a=
bout business and finance and technology =E2=80=94=C2=A0for people to think=
