king model. Surely Musk=E2=80=99s bankers at Morgan Stanley had their own f=
inancial models that they could have shared with him (and probably tried to=
!), not least because they committed for a lot of debt financing, and *bank=
s* don't do that without a financial model.


  [2] =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re never happy with the amount you traded,=E2=80=
=9D is Agustin Lebron=E2=80=99s  second law of trading. If you say =E2=80=
=9CElon I=E2=80=99m in for any size=E2=80=9D and he cuts you in for a small=
 slice, then you wish it was bigger, but at least you can expect to make a =
large return on your small slice, because lots of people are clamoring to i=
nvest with him and (1) probably they=E2=80=99re right and (2) in any case i=
f they=E2=80=99re wrong you can probably flip your slice to one of them for=
 a profit. If he cuts you in for a very very large slice then that means th=
at no one else is clamoring to invest with him, which probably means you=E2=
=80=99re missing something.


  [3] Most importantly, it ignores recovery value. in real CDS, if there is=
 a default, you pay me the $100, but I give you back $100 face amount of th=
e issuer=E2=80=99s bonds. (Because traditionally CDS was about insuring bon=
ds against default risk; I own bonds and want to hedge against the risk of =
default, and when there is a default I give you the bonds and you give me t=
he money.) Those bonds are not going to be worth $100, because the issuer i=
s in default, but they probably won=E2=80=99t be worth $0 either: You=E2=80=
=99ll be able to get some money out of the bankrupt issuer. It is a convent=
ion to assume that the =E2=80=9Crecovery=E2=80=9D on default will be about =
40 cents on the dollar (so $40 here), though in reality it will vary widely=
. There are other important things missing from this simple model. Modern C=
DS pays standardized running spreads and points up front, so in practice I =
will pay more of the premium to you at the beginning and less as a running =
spread over time; this is an important difference if you think that the pro=
bability of default is not evenly spaced over the five-year term. And in pr=
actice CDS will generally cash settle based on an auction of bonds that det=
ermines the recovery price, and there are shenanigans possible there. And o=
f course most CDS bets make or lose money based on changes in spread rather=
 than on actual realized defaults; you can reasonably buy CDS to bet =E2=80=
=9CI think the market=E2=80=99s view of this company=E2=80=99s creditworthi=
ness will deteriorate=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9CI think this company wi=
ll go bankrupt.=E2=80=9D What I say in the text is the broad general intuit=
ion for what CDS *is*, but if you actually trade CDS based only on this int=
uition you=E2=80=99ll get your face ripped off a lot. If you actually trade=
 CDS you need to know the real mechanics.


  [4] Bloomberg=E2=80=99s CDSW page will give you a more standard-model cal=
culation of implied probability of default from CDS prices, though you will=
 need to put in a recovery assumption to have this probability be meaningfu=
l. (And it will be the implied probability over the CDS term, not per year.=
)


