<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An oversimplified but useful description of a =
credit default swap is that it is a bet that some company will default on i=
ts debt. We make this bet for some period of time, say five years, and I pa=
y you $X per year, which is called the =E2=80=9Cpremium=E2=80=9D or more of=
ten the =E2=80=9CCDS spread.=E2=80=9D And then if the company defaults duri=
ng the five years, you pay me back $100. And if it doesn=E2=80=99t, you pay=
 me nothing and keep the spread.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is wrong in lots of important ways that I=
 am simply not going to discuss here, and I will ignore your emails pointin=
g them out, but it is=C2=A0<em>roughly=C2=A0</em>right.<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It is right to within, you know, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/29250431.285527/aHR0cHM6Ly9vbmxpbmVsaWJyYXJ5LndpbG=
V5LmNvbS9kb2kvZnVsbC8xMC4xMTExL2ouMTU0MC02MjYxLjE5ODYudGIwNDUxMy54/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB2fde65ea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a factor of two</a>,=C2=A0maybe a facto=
r of four. One thing that this crude model is useful for is getting=C2=A0a=
=C2=A0rough but immediate intuition for what CDS spreads mean about the pro=
bability of default. If you promise to pay me $100 if a company defaults, a=
nd in exchange you charge me $X per year, X/100 is=C2=A0<em>in the ballpark=
=C2=A0</em>of your expected probability that the company will default this =
year. Oh it=E2=80=99s not really a good probability estimate, don=E2=80=99t=
 go trading CDS on this intuition, and don=E2=80=99t email me to point out =
the nuances that it misses.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But it=E2=80=99s the right order of magnitude. If you think that =
a company is basically a coin flip to default this year, you will not sell =
me $100 of CDS for $5: Half the time, you will have to pay out $100, and th=
e $5 premium does not cover that. If you think that a company is vanishingl=
y unlikely to default this year, you might sell me $100 of CDS for $1, or $=
0.50, or even less. Apple Inc. five-year CDS will run you about 30 basis po=
ints, or $0.30 per year for $100 of coverage. The people selling that CDS d=
o not think that Apple will default. The people buying that CDS don=E2=80=
=99t think that either; they have other reasons for making this bet, which =
they fully expect to lose.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of 9 a.m. New York time today, five-year CD=
S on Credit Suisse Group AG was trading at about 350=C2=A0basis points, mea=
ning roughly =E2=80=94=C2=A0roughly! =E2=80=94=C2=A0that I would have to pa=
y you $3.50=C2=A0per year for this bet, and you=E2=80=99d pay me $100 if Cr=
edit Suisse defaults. What does this tell you about the market-implied prob=
ability that Credit Suisse will default on its debt? Well, Credit Suisse CD=
S was trading at about 250 basis points on Friday,=C2=A0 about 135 in June,=
 about 57 at the start of the year. So it tells you that the market-implied=
 probability of default has gone=C2=A0<em>up=C2=A0</em>a lot. But it is sti=
ll absolutely=C2=A0<em>low</em>. You would not charge me $3.50 per year for=
 $100 of insurance against Credit Suisse defaulting unless you thought the =
chances of that happening were slim.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course markets can be wrong, and sometimes =
companies bop along with quite low CDS spreads and then one day default on =
their debts. (This is particularly a risk for financial companies, which te=
nd to default because of sudden bank runs=C2=A0rather than long slow busine=
ss deterioration.) But a weird thing happened this weekend where people loo=
ked at the chart of Credit Suisse CDS prices, saw them going up a lot, <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29250431.285527/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNjEwNGE2OTktZmE3Zi00YTgxLTljMzUtYTlhMmY4ZmY5M=
mQy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB19f67dc6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> and said</a> =E2=80=9CAha! =
This proves that Credit Suisse is in distress!=E2=80=9D But, no. It proves =
that a=C2=A0number went up a lot, but remains, in the scheme of things, low=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand the problem with stuff like =
this is that then Credit Suisse has to put out a statement saying that ever=
ything is fine, and nothing is worse for a bank than putting out a statemen=
t saying that everything is fine. (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/29250431.285527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZWNvbmxpYi5vcmcvbGlicmFyeS=
9CYWdlaG90L2JhZ0xvbS5odG1sP2NoYXB0ZXJfbnVtPTUjYm9vay1yZWFkZXI/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB23b0e579" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Bagehot</a>:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CEvery banker knows=
 that if he has to prove that he is worthy of credit, however good may be h=
is arguments, in fact his credit is gone.=E2=80=9D) <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29250431.285527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMDMvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1tYXJrZXQtdHVy=
bW9pbC1kZWVwZW5zLWFmdGVyLWNlby1tZW1vLWJhY2tmaXJlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDAzMjJfTU9=
ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT=
0yMjEwMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdbd62820=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">  Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse Group AG was plunged into fresh =
market turmoil after Chief Executive Officer Ulrich Koerner=E2=80=99s attem=
pts to reassure employees and investors backfired, adding to uncertainty su=
rrounding the bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The stock, which had already more than halved =
this year before Monday=E2=80=99s sell-off, fell as much as 12% in Zurich t=
rading to a record low that values the firm at less than $10 billion. That =
was accompanied by a spike in the cost to insure the bank=E2=80=99s debt ag=
ainst default, which jumped to its highest ever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Koerner, for the second time in as many weeks,=
 had sought to calm employees and the markets with a memo late Friday stres=
sing the bank=E2=80=99s liquidity and capital strength. Instead, it focused=
 attention on the dramatic recent moves in the firm=E2=80=99s stock price a=
nd credit spreads, and investors rushed for the exit when trading reopened =
after the weekend.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While acknowledging that the bank was at a =E2=
=80=9Ccritical moment,=E2=80=9D he pledged to send employees regular update=
s until the firm announces its new strategic plan on Oct. 27. At the same t=
ime, Credit Suisse again sent around talking points to executives dealing w=
ith clients who brought up the credit default swap, according to people wit=
h knowledge of the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While those are still far from distressed -- a=
nd also part of a broad market selloff -- they signify deteriorating percep=
tions of creditworthiness for the scandal-hit bank in the current environme=
nt.=C2=A0 ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, some prominent figures took to Twitter =
over the weekend to dismiss some of the rumors circulating on social media =
prompted by the widened CDS spread as =E2=80=9Cscaremongering.=E2=80=9D Sab=
a Capital Management=E2=80=99s Boaz Weinstein tweeted =E2=80=9Ctake a deep =
breath=E2=80=9D and compared the situation to when Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s=
 CDS was twice as wide in 2011 and 2012.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the Wall Street Journal <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29250431.285527/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3Nq=
LmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWhhcy1uby10aW1lLXRvLWxvc2UtMTE2NjQ4MDA=
1NzI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3bdbd719" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> notes</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The beleaguered lender=E2=80=99s s=
hare price fell around 8% in early trading on Monday. The apparent trigger =
for the latest selloff was nothing more than its bankers calling customers =
and investors this weekend to reassure them that all is in hand despite a j=
ump in its credit-default swaps on Friday.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah, no, high on the list of calls that you n=
ever want to get is =E2=80=9Chi, this is your bank, we just wanted to tell =
you that everything is fine here, how are you?=E2=80=9D</p>
