 worth $0 either: You=E2=80=99ll be able to get some money out of the bankr=
upt issuer. It is a convention to assume that the =E2=80=9Crecovery=E2=80=
=9D on default will be about 40 cents on the dollar (so $40 here), though i=
n reality it will vary widely. There are other important things missing fro=
m this simple model. Modern CDS pays standardized running spreads and point=
s up front, so in practice I will pay more of the premium to you at the beg=
inning and less as a running spread over time; this is an important differe=
nce if you think that the probability of default is not evenly spaced over =
the five-year term. And in practice CDS will generally cash settle based on=
 an auction of bonds that determines the recovery price, and there are shen=
anigans possible there. And of course most CDS bets make or lose money base=
d on changes in spread rather than on actual realized defaults; you can rea=
sonably buy CDS to bet =E2=80=9CI think the market=E2=80=99s view of this c=
ompany=E2=80=99s creditworthiness will deteriorate=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=
=80=9CI think this company will go bankrupt.=E2=80=9D What I say in the tex=
t is the broad general intuition for what CDS *is*, but if you actually tra=
de CDS based only on this intuition you=E2=80=99ll get your face ripped off=
 a lot. If you actually trade CDS you need to know the real mechanics.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] Bloomberg=E2=80=99s CDSW page will give yo=
u a more standard-model calculation of implied probability of default from =
CDS prices, though you will need to put in a recovery assumption to have th=
is probability be meaningful. (And it will be the implied probability over =
the CDS term, not per year.)</p>
</div>
